<br>
(Vary depending on BIOS version)<br>
At boot, when memory is counting, press DEL (or F1 on some BIOS).<br>
<br>
Go in the password section, setup a supervisor password, and set it to ask at boot time.<br>
<br>
Save config.<br>
<br>
To remove it at later time, simply enter BIOS, go in password section, and change the password to blank, it will disable it.<br>
<br>
Works for most AWARD and AMIBIOS bios...<br>
<br>
Careful about what you do in the BIOS section, as alot of stuff in there is sensible. If you are REALLY cpu-ignorant, then maybe ask a friend to set it up for you (not your roommates)<br>
<br>
Another method wayyyy more safe is to go in User and Password in the control panel, and set a password on your username, and set it to ask at OS boot time. Look carefully at the checkboxes and options in that screen, and set it up appropriately. Be careful to REMEMBER your password, else, you're screwed.<br>
