<br>
Actually, if you use a screensaver, just choose the option to password protect your screen.<br>
<br>
In NT/2000/XP, this option is integrated with whatever logon/password you logged into the OS with.<br>
<br>
Sadly, XP Home does set people up to use null password accounts. Once you do enable a password on your account, you will notice a slight behavior change when you press cntrl-alt-delete. Right now, you'd go directly to the Task Manager. Once you set a password, you'll get an options screen that allows you to change password, log off, lock workstation, shutdown pc, go to task mgr, and cancel.<br>
<br>
Also, and this is VERY important. Consider setting a password on the administrator account. Otherwise one of your roomates could forcibly log you off of your session just by typing in Administrator without a password.<br>
<br>
For those of you running 98 or ME, I don't recommend doing any ofthis, as the password is stored seperately, and the feature isn't very 'graceful'.  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=381929"> Naladini </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
